PHI WORD CREATION CONSTRAINTS - NON-NEGOTIABLE:
ONLY consonants: h,k,l,m,n,p,r,s,t,w + fricatives: ph,th,sh,wh
ALL syllables: CV structure (consonant+vowel, open syllables only)
ALL initial syllables MUST start with consonant/fricative
NO duplicate syllables in same word

PHI VOWEL HIATUS RULES:
Vowel pairs (like au, ei, oa) are ALWAYS pronounced in hiatus (separate syllables)
au = /a.u/ with syllables ["a", "u"] - NOT ["au"]
noukai = /no.u.ka.i/ with syllables ["no", "u", "ka", "i"] - NOT ["nou", "kai"]
The second vowel in a vowel pair forms its own syllable with explicit syllable boundary
If a word contains a vowel pair, the syllable that contains the first vowel of the pair must have either a consonant or fricative digraph onset only. 

STRESS / SYLLABLE EMPHASIS RULE:
- By default, stress falls on the penultimate (second-to-last) syllable of a word.
- Exception: in disyllabic (two-syllable) words, stress falls on the initial (first) syllable.

IMPORTANT:
Build from Phi sounds first, concept second. Show your work: list sounds chosen, verify syllable pattern, check all rules before declaring valid.

Ensure a variety of consonant, vowel, fricative digraph and vowel pair usage. ROTATE the use of each of these. Never create a set of words all ending in the same vowel. As well, when generating content words, vary between two-syllable and three-syllable words, favouring two-syllable words.

